[
    {
        "content": "<p>For a group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>, the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holomorph_(mathematics)\">holomorph</a> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hol}(G)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hol</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is simply defined as the semidirect product <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>⋊</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G \\rtimes \\mathrm{Aut}(G)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.765em;vertical-align:-0.0817em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin amsrm\">⋊</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Aut</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. I recently saw the definition from Dummit--Foote and realized that it does not exist in mathlib yet. It is fairly easy to formalize the definition (since we already have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/GroupTheory/SemidirectProduct.html#SemidirectProduct\">semidirect product</a>) but not sure if it worths to add assuming I don't have any nice theorems / applications using it. (Dummit--Foote include some computations for small <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>.) What's usual practice in such case?</p>",
        "id": 547566048,
        "sender_full_name": "Seewoo Lee",
        "timestamp": 1761677032
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"588998\">@Seewoo Lee</span> I don't speak for mathlib, but I think usually mathlib wouldn't include it in this case.</p>",
        "id": 547572190,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761679212
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess it depends - I don't think you need Big Results<span aria-label=\"trademark\" class=\"emoji emoji-2122\" role=\"img\" title=\"trademark\">:trademark:</span>, but you'd be expected to have at least some basic lemmas about the definition so you can actually use it</p>",
        "id": 547600603,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1761691410
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, probably I will think of some basic facts (things on wikipedia or textbooks). There are some big(?) theorems using it but haven’t looked in details.</p>",
        "id": 547601059,
        "sender_full_name": "Seewoo Lee",
        "timestamp": 1761691689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>At least, we can introduce it as an <code>abbrev</code> so that <code>loogle</code> can find it.</p>",
        "id": 547613196,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1761700982
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>is that how loogle works?</p>",
        "id": 547649602,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761725302
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A basic fact you could try formalizing is that, as a subgroup of Perm(G), the holomorph is equal to the normalizer of the left regular subgroup.</p>",
        "id": 547939343,
        "sender_full_name": "Scott Carnahan",
        "timestamp": 1761831939
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>how do you embed it into Perm(G)?</p>",
        "id": 547940827,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761832312
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>G acts by left multiplication, and Aut(G) acts by automorphisms.</p>",
        "id": 548016092,
        "sender_full_name": "Scott Carnahan",
        "timestamp": 1761851780
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think this map already should be in mathlib (cc <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"588998\">@Seewoo Lee</span>)</p>",
        "id": 548016989,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1761852077
    }
